@node RX_About

@{b}About@{ub}

Purpose: Display the About requester.

Syntax : About (no parameters)

Example: about
@endnode

@node RX_Active

@{b}Active@{ub}

Purpose: Set the active entry in the list.

Syntax : Active EVENT/S,TASK/S,NOTE/S,ENTRY/N,NOACTIVE/S

ENTRY/N    - Number of the entry in the list (1...n).
NOACTIVE/S - Flag to de-activate the list (eg. no entry active).
             This has no effect on selected entries.

Example: active 5
         active noactive
@endnode

@node RX_CalDate

@{b}CalDate@{ub}

Purpose: Set the date for a Calendar Window.

Syntax : CalDate CALENDAR/N/A,STRING/F/A

CALENDAR/N/A - The ID number of the Calendar Window to set.
STRING/F/A   - A @{"date string" link Dates}. 

Example: caldate 1 2440637
         caldate 2 19 2 70
         caldate 1 19 feb 1970
         caldate -1 month
         caldate 5 week
@endnode

@node RX_Calendar

@{b}Calendar@{ub}

Purpose: Create a new Calendar Window.

Syntax : Calendar ID/N/K,FRAME/K,FONT/K,BACKDROP/S,NOBORDER/S,HIDEDATE/S,WEEKNUMBERS/S,HIDEEVENTS/S,DATE/F

ID/N/K        - Every Calendar Window has a unique ID number that is used when MUI does a window snapshot. You can use this number to open a Calendar Window with a special ID that was previously snapshoted at a particular place.
FRAME/K       - A string indicating the MUI Frame to use around the Calendar in the Window. This string is language dependent. The full list of names can be seen by looking at the Frame Cycle gadget in the Calendar Configuration Page You only need to type enough of the name to separate it from another string.
FONT/K        - Font name and size separated by forward slash '/'.
BACKDROP/S    - Open the window in backdrop mode.
NOBORDER/S    - Remove window borders, as well as month and year gadgets.
HIDEDATE/S    - Hide the Date Object in the window.
WEEKNUMBERS/S - Display weeknumbers in the Calendar.
HIDEEVENTS    - Don't show Events in Calendar display.
DATE/F        - The rest of the line is interpretted as a @{"date" link Dates}.

Example:
         calendar
         calendar id 2 2440637
         calendar id 2 19 feb 70
         calendar font helvetica/11 august
@endnode

@node RX_ClearList

@{b}ClearList@{ub}

Purpose: Clear the contents of the Event or Task list (or both).

Syntax : ClearList EVENT/S,TASK/S,NOTE/S,ALL/S

ALL/S - Clear ALL data (Events and Tasks).

Example: clearlist
         clearlist event
         clearlist all
@endnode

@node RX_CloseCalendars

@{b}CloseCalendars@{ub}

Purpose: Close all Calendar Windows.

Syntax : CloseCalendars (no parameters)

Example: closecalendars
@endnode

@node RX_Copy

@{b}Copy@{ub}

Purpose: To make an exact duplicate of an existing Event or Task.

Syntax : EVENT/S,TASK/S,NOTE/S,ENTRY/N

ENTRY/N  - Number of the entry in the list (1 to Entries) to copy. If you do not specify ENTRY then the current Active entry will be used.

Example: copy
         copy 2
@endnode

@node RX_DateInfo

@{b}DateInfo@{ub}

Purpose: Return some information on a given date.
         If you call this command with no parameters (apart form the date) then a new @{"Information Window" link InformationWindows} will be opened.

Syntax : DateInfo WEEKDAY/S,DAY/S,MONTH/S,YEAR/S,JULIAN/S,MJD/S,DOY/S,WOY/S,TILL/S,MOONPHASE/N/K,DATE/S,STRING/F

WEEKDAY/S     - number from 0 to 6 indicating the weekday of the calendar. 0 might equal a different day of the week depending upon the Locale settings, e.g. 0 might equal Sunday or Monday.
DAY/S         - number from 1 to 31 depending upon the month.
MONTH/S       - number from 1 to 12
YEAR/S        - four digit number, e.g. 1996
JULIAN/S      - astronomical Julian Day number, e.g. 2440637
MJD/S         - Modified Julian Day number, e.g. 40636
DOY/S         - day of the year, e.g. you could find out how many days in a year by specifying a date '31 dec 96'.
WOY/S         - week of the year. 0 = last week of previous year, 1 to 52 that year, 53 = first week of proceeding year.
MOONPHASE/N/K - returns the date (in the global configured format) of the next specified moon phase. Specify: 1 for New Moon, 2 for First Quarter, 3 for New Moon, 4 for Last Quarter.
DATE/S        - returns the interpreted date in the global configured format, e.g. you call 'dateinfo date today' and you receive '12 May 96'.
STRING/F/A    - the date to get information on. It may be in any of the accepted @{"formats" link Dates}. This will default to the present day's date if no string is parsed.

Sorry, but you may specify only one of the previous switches at one time.

Example: dateinfo
         dateinfo today
         dateinfo date tomorrow
            tomorrowsdate = result
         dateinfo date -1 month
            datelastmonth = result
         dateinfo weekday today
         dateinfo woy 1 1 1996
         dateinfo moonphase 1
            nextnewmoon = result
@endnode

@node RX_Edit

@{b}Edit@{ub}

Purpose: Open an Edit Window for the currently active entry in a respective list.

Syntax : Active EVENT/S,ALARM/S,TASK/S

EVENT/S - The Event Edit Window.
ALARM/S - The Alarm Edit Window.
TASK/S  - The Task Edit Window.

Example: edit alarm
@endnode

@node RX_Filter

@{b}Filter@{ub}

Purpose: Set (or toggle) the Event or Task list filter on or off.

Syntax : Filter EVENT/S,TASK/S,STATE/N

STATE/N  - A value of 0 will switch the filter off and any other value will turn it on. If you don't specify the STATE command then the state will be toggled.

Example: filter event
         filter event 0
@endnode

@node RX_FilterDate

@{b}FilterDate@{ub}

Purpose: Set the Filter Date for the Event or Task list.

Syntax : FilterDate EVENT/S,TASK/S,STRING/F/A

STRING/F/A - The string to be interpreted as a date.

Example: filterdate 2440637
         filterdate 19 feb 70
@endnode

@node RX_FilterString

@{b}FilterString@{ub}

Purpose: Set the Filter String for the Event or Task list.

Syntax : FilterString EVENT/S,TASK/S,STRING/F

STRING/F/A - The filter string.

Example: filterstring event mn tv#?
         filterstring task overdue
@endnode

@node RX_GetActive

@{b}GetActive@{ub}

Purpose: Return the number of the currently active entry in a list.

Syntax : GetActive EVENT/S,TASK/S,NOTE/S
 
Example: getactive event
         active_event = result
@endnode

@node RX_GetCalDate

@{b}GetCalDate@{ub}

Purpose: Return the date from a given Calendar Window.

Syntax : GetCalDate CALENDAR/N/A,FORMAT/N/K,JULIAN/S

CALENDAR/N/A - The ID number of the Calendar Window to retrieve date from.
FORMAT/N/K   - Number of a format used to return date (@{"range" link Config_GeneralDTFormat}: 1 to 6).
JULIAN/S     - Switch to cause date to be returned as a Julian Day number.

Example: getcaldate 1
         getcaldate 2 julian
         getcaldate 1 format 4
@endnode

@node RX_GetEntries

@{b}GetEntries@{ub}

Purpose: Return the number of the shown entries in a list.

Syntax : GetEntries EVENT/S,TASK/S,NOTE/S,TOTAL/S,TITLES/S

TOTAL/S  - Return the total number of Events or Tasks, not just the ones shown.
TITLES/S - Return the number of Day Titles displayed in the list. A title might look like "Monday, 10 March 1997".

Example: getentries event
         shown_events = result
         
         getentries task total
         total_tasks = result
@endnode

@node RX_GetField

@{b}GetField@{ub}

Purpose: Return the value of a data field for an Event or Task.

Syntax : GetField EVENT/S,TASK/S,NOTE/S,ENTRY/N/K,FIELD/N

ENTRY/N/K - Number of the entry in the displayed list (1...n). This means that the number will not always refer to the same Event! It refers to the number of the Event in the list currently shown. If you specify no ENTRY command then the active entry is used.
TYPE/S    - This is an IMPORTANT parameter. The reason for this is that it enables you to determine if an entry in the displayed list is a Title or an actual Event/Task. A result of 0 indicates that the item is a Title, 1 indicates an Event or Task. See example below.
FIELD/N   - The number of the data field to affect (see @{"SetField" link RX_SetField}).

Example: getfield type
         type = result
         if (type = 0) then
            say 'This is a title'
         else
            say 'This is an event or task.'
                  
         getfield task entry 1 1
         task_name = result
@endnode

@node RX_GetFilter

@{b}GetFilter@{ub}

Purpose: Return the state of the Filter for the Event or Task lists.

Syntax : GetFilter EVENT/S,TASK/S

Example: getfilter
         getfilter task
@endnode

@node RX_GetFilterDate

@{b}GetFilterDate@{ub}

Purpose: Return the date of the Event or Task Filter.

Syntax : GetFilterDate EVENT/S,TASK/S,FORMAT/N/K,JULIAN/S

FORMAT/N/K - Number of a format used to return date (@{"range" link Config_GeneralDTFormat}: 1 to 6).
JULIAN/S   - Switch to cause date to be returned as a Julian Day number.

Example: getfilterdate
         getfilterdate format 2
         getfilterdate julian
@endnode

@node RX_GetFilterString

@{b}GetFilterString@{ub}

Purpose: Return the Event or Task Filter string.

Syntax : GetFilterString EVENT/S,TASK/S

Example: getfilterstring
         getfilterstring event
@endnode

@node RX_GetInfo

@{b}GetInfo@{ub}

Purpose: Return some global information.

Syntax : GetInfo DATEFORMAT/S,DATESEP/S,TIMEFORMAT/S,TIMESEP/S

DATEFORMAT/S - Return the current Date Format (@{"range" link Config_GeneralOptions} 1 to 6).
DATESEP/S    - Return the current Date Separator character. This is a one character length string. You could use this to parse dates @{"retrieved" link RX_GetCalDate} from Calendar Windows.
TIMEFORMAT/S - Return the current Time Format (1 = 12 Hour, 2 = 24 Hour).
TIMESEP/S    - Return the current Tiem Separator character. This is a one character length string.

Example: getinfo dateformat
@endnode

@node RX_GetSelect

@{b}GetSelect@{ub}

Purpose: Return the selection state of an entry or a list.

Syntax : GetSelect EVENT/S,TASK/S,NOTE/S,ACTIVE/S
 
ACTIVE/S - Get the selection state of the Active entry in a list; otherwise return the number of selected entries in a list.
 
Example: getselect active
         active_state = result
         
         getselect
         selected_entries = result
@endnode

@node RX_InitCalendars

@{b}InitCalendars@{ub}

Purpose: Close all current Calendar Windows and re-open the default ones.

Syntax : InitCalendars (no parameters)
 
Example: initcalendars
@endnode

@node RX_LastSaved

@{b}LastSaved@{ub}

Purpose: Perform the normal LastSaved operation.
         Restore the Event and Task lists to previous settings in ENVARC:

Syntax : LastSaved (no parameters)
 
Example: lastsaved
@endnode

@node RX_ListFormat

@{b}ListFormat@{ub}

Purpose: Describe the format for the Event or Task lists.

Syntax : ListFormat EVENT/S,TASK/S,NOTE/S,FORMAT/F

FORMAT/F - The new format for the list.
 
Example: listformat col=2,col=3,col=0
@endnode

@node RX_ListQuiet

@{b}ListQuiet@{ub}

Purpose: Temporarily stop a list from being updated/redrawn.
         If you are performing a lot of operations a list then it is probably a good idea to make a list Quiet during this period. This way operations on the list won't be slowed down by the list redrawing itself. Make sure you turn the ListQuiet option off after you finish whatever you were doing.

Syntax : ListQuiet EVENT/S,TASK/S,STATE/N

STATE/N  - The state of the list. Non zero values set it quiet.

Example: listquiet event state 0
         ...do a lot of work like adding or editing entries
         listquiet event state 1
@endnode

@node RX_MainGadgets

@{b}MainGadgets@{ub}

Purpose: Toggle or set the state of the Main Gadgets.

Syntax : MainGadgets STATE/N

STATE/N  - A value of 0 will make the gadgets disappear and any other value will make them appear. If you don't specify the STATE command then the state will be toggled.

Example: maingadgets
         maingadgets 1
@endnode

@node RX_MainWindow

@{b}MainWindow@{ub}

Purpose: Toggle or set the state of the Main Window.

Syntax : MainWindow STATE/N

STATE/N  - A value of 0 will close the window and any other value will open it. If you don't specify the STATE command then the state will be toggled.

Example: mainwindow
         mainwindow 1
@endnode

@node RX_New

@{b}New@{ub}

Purpose: Create a new Event, Task, or Note.
         The Edit Window for the respective type will not open and you may edit it via the @{"SetField" link RX_SetField} command.

Syntax : New EVENT/S,TASK/S,NOTE/S
 
Example: new task
@endnode

@node RX_Open

@{b}Open@{ub}

Purpose: Open a valid On-Time list file.

Syntax : Open FILE,MERGE_EVENTS/S,MERGE_TASKS/S,MERGE_NOTES/S,MERGE_ALL/S

FILE           - Full name and path of the file to be loaded.
MERGE_EVENTS/S - Merge Events from the file with the current Event list in memory.
MERGE_TASKS/S  - Merge Tasks from the file with the current Task list in memory.
MERGE_NOTES/S  - MErge Notes from the file with the current Note list in memory.
MERGE_ALL      - Merge both Events and Tasks from the file with the current lists in memory.

Example: open "ram:testfile.list" merge_all
@endnode

@node RX_PrintData

@{b}PrintData@{ub}

Purpose: Print the displayed Event or Task list to a specified output.

Syntax : PrintData EVENT/S,TASK/S,NOTE/S,OUTPUT/F

OUTPUT/F - The output device/file. If this is not specified then "PRT:" is used.

Example: printdata
         printdata task ram:tasklist.txt
         printdata event "ram:event list.txt"
@endnode

@node RX_Remove

@{b}Remove@{ub}

Purpose: Remove all currently selected entries (or single Active) from a list.

Syntax : Remove EVENT/S,TASK/S,NOTE/S,ACTIVE/S

ACTIVE/S - Switch to cause only active entry to be removed. Otherwise ALL the SELECTED entries are removed

Example: remove
         removed = result
@endnode

@node RX_Requester

@{b}Requester@{ub}

Purpose: Display a configurable requester for information or request purposes.
         It returns a number indicating which button was pressed. The actual numbering of the buttons is 1, 2, ..., n, 0.

Syntax : Requester TITLE/K,BUTTON/K,MESSAGE/F
 
Example: requester "This is a message."
         requester title "A User Message" button "Fine" "This is just to say hello"
         requester title "A Question" button "*_Amiga|_pc" "What computer do you like?"
            answer = result /* "Amiga" would return 1, "pc" would return 0 */
@endnode

@node RX_Restore

@{b}Restore@{ub}

Purpose: Perform the normal Restore operation.
         Restore the Event and Tasks lists to previous settings in ENV:

Syntax : Restore (no parameters)
 
Example: restore
@endnode

@node RX_RX

@{b}RX@{ub}

Purpose: Invoke an ARexx script from within Alarmist. Meaning that the script's host address is set to "ONTIME".

Syntax : RX FILE

FILE - Full name of the file to be executed.

Example: rx 'rexx:test_script.rexx'
@endnode

@node RX_Save

@{b}Save@{ub}

Purpose: Perform the same function as the Save button in the Main Window.

Syntax : Save (no parameters)
 
Example: save
@endnode

@node RX_SaveAs

@{b}SaveAs@{ub}

Purpose: Saves the current Event and Task lists to a specified file.

Syntax : SaveAs FILE,ICON/S

FILE   - Full name of the file to be saved.
ICON/S - Flag to indicate whether a preset icon is to be created for this saved file.

Example: saveas "ram:testfile.list" icon
@endnode

@node RX_Search

@{b}Search@{ub}

Purpose: Search the Event or Task list for a string.

Syntax : Search EVENT/S,TASK/S,CASESENS/S,FIELD/N/K,STRING/F/A

CASESENS/S - Turn on case sensitive searching.
FIELD      - Field number to search (described below).
STRING     - The search string.

The Event field numbers are:

0 - All Fields
1 - Name
2 - Notes
3 - Begin Date
4 - End Date
5 - Begin Time
6 - End Time

The Task field numbers are:

0 - All Fields
1 - Name
2 - Notes
3 - Begin Date
4 - End Date

Example: search hello
         search event casesens hello
         search event casesens field 1 hello
@endnode

@node RX_Select

@{b}Select@{ub}

Purpose: Set the selection state of one or all entries in a list.

Syntax : Select EVENT/S,TASK/S,NOTE/S,ENTRY/N,ALL/S,DESELECT/S

ENTRY/N    - Number of the entry in the list (1...n).
ALL/S      - Affect the entire list.
DESELECT/S - Deselect instead of selecting.

Example: select 1
         select all
         select 1 deselect
         select all deselect
@endnode

@node RX_SetField

@{b}SetField@{ub}

Purpose: Set a field for an Event or a Task.

Syntax : SetField EVENT/S,TASK/S,NOTE/S,ENTRY/N/K,FIELD/N,VALUE/F

ENTRY/N/K - Number of the entry in the list (1...n). This means that the number will not always refer to the same Event! It refers to the number of the Event in the list currently shown. If you specify no ENTRY command then the active entry is used.
FIELD/N   - The number of the data field to affect (described below).
VALUE/F   - The new value for this field

The Event field numbers are:

 1 - Name (up to 128 characters)
 2 - Notes (up to 128 characters)
 3 - Begin Date {Valid @{"date" link Dates} string}
 4 - Event Date {Valid @{"date" link Dates} string}
 5 - Begin Time {Valid @{"time" link Times} string}
 6 - End Time   {Valid @{"time" link Times} string}
 7 - Repeat Type {0 = None, 1 = Days, 2 = Weeks, 3 = Months, 4 = Years}
 8 - Repeat Amount {0 to ...}
 9 - Repeat on the same day and week of the Begin month.
10 - Repeat Until Date {Valid @{"date" link Dates} string}
11 - Delete when old {0 = OFF, !0 = ON}
12 - Passive {0 = OFF, !0 = ON}
13 - Remind Days {0 to ...}
14 - Alarm Execution Type {1 = CLI, 2 = WB, 3 = AREXX}
15 - Alarm Execution String (up to 256 characters)
16 - Snooze Execution Type {1 = CLI, 2 = WB, 3 = AREXX}
17 - Snooze Execution String (up to 256 characters)
18 - Snooze Seconds (up to 1800)
19 - Snooze Repeats {0 to 99, 100 = INFINITE}
20 - Everyday Alarm {0 = OFF, !0 = ON}
21 - End Alarm {0 = OFF, !0 = ON}
22 - Alarm Log Popup {0 = OFF, !0 = ON}
23 - Alarm Warn Type {0 = OFF, 1 = GLOBAL, 2 = LOCAL}
24 - Alarm Warn Time {0 = GLOBAL, 1 to 100}

The Task field numbers are:

 1 - Name (up to 128 characters)
 2 - Notes (up to 128 characters)
 3 - Begin Date
 4 - Event Date
 5 - Priority {0 = Lowest, 1 = Low, 2 = Normal, 3 = High, 4 = Highest}

The Note field numbers are:

 1 - Note String (up to 128 characters)
 2 - Date

Example: setfield event 1 Event Name
         setfield task entry 1 Task Name
@endnode

@node RX_Toggle

@{b}Toggle@{ub}

Purpose: Toggle the state of selected Events or Tasks. Toggling an Event changes its activation state: a Task completion state is toggled.

Syntax : Toggle EVENT/S,TASK/S,STATE/N

STATE/N  - A value of 0 will toggle selected entries off and any other value will turn them on. If you don't specify the STATE command then the state will be toggled.

Example: toggle 
         toggle state 1
@endnode

@node RX_Update

@{b}Update@{ub}

Purpose: Redraws Calendars and lists. This is useful if for example the date is changed and the program should redraw date sensitive items.

Syntax : Update (no parameters)
 
Example: update
@endnode

@node RX_Use

@{b}Use@{ub}

Purpose: Perform the same function as the Use button in the Main Window.

Syntax : Use (no parameters)
 
Example: use
@endnode

@remark --- END FILE ---
